they’re not literally the same but both can basically be proved with the flavor of diagonalization

Godels proof is something like 
- map each equation to a unique natural number
- map equation that determines if some equation proves another equation to a natural number 
- uh oh we can create a formula that can be proved and not be proved 
(flavor of “this statement is false”)

If we could have a computer determine that if any given equation is true or not (decision/halting problem), this would contradict Godel. But we can also prove that this sort of machine is impossible using almost exactly the steps as above
Ok the problem is we’ve simplified things and brushed over consistency of a system. So we need some results beyond the above proof of godels to actually prove incompleteness
Here’s a good blog post on this I just found but basically it shows why we need something stronger than just TM undecidability to show the entire version of godels ScottAaronson.blog/?p=710

yea diagonalization is a bad name. The intuition I keep for it is 
- take a set of all elements of type X 
- append an element that is of type X but also not of type X
